## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why This Breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — there is no way to forcibly terminate a managed thread. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Pattern Classification

| Original Code | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `while (_running)` + `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `IsCancellationRequested`, decide to continue |
| `GetNextItem()` (blocking) | Blocking call interruption | Pass token to unblock |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — mirrors the old ThreadAbortException block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed; loop condition exits naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after timeout, you cannot force-kill it.
        // The thread will exit at its next cancellation checkpoint.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Key Changes to `GetNextItem`

The blocking `GetNextItem()` **must** become cancellation-aware, otherwise cancellation stalls until it returns naturally:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
private WorkItem GetNextItem() 
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER: unblocks when token is cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If using a `ManualResetEvent` or similar wait:
```csharp
// Replace event.WaitOne() with:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle });
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---|---|
| Not passing `token` to `GetNextItem` | Thread blocks forever — `Stop()` never completes |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Timer/callback memory leaks |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` without `when` filter | Swallows unrelated cancellations from inner calls |
| Expecting instant stop after `Cancel()` | Cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint — design accordingly |
| Using `Thread.Sleep` in the loop | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so cancellation wakes it |

### Behavioral Difference

| Aspect | .NET Framework (`Thread.Abort`) | .NET 8 (Cooperative) |
|---|---|---|
| Interrupts blocked code? | Yes (injects exception anywhere) | Only at explicit checkpoints |
| Guaranteed stop timing? | ~Immediate | Depends on checkpoint frequency |
| Risk of corrupted state? | High (exception at any IL instruction) | Low (only at safe points) |
| Cleanup reliability | `finally` may not run if abort is re-raised | `finally` always runs |

The cooperative model is **safer** but requires that every blocking call in the chain accepts and respects the `CancellationToken`.
